<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911223-0039</DOCNO><DOCID>911223-0039.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Martin Marietta Corp.:   Company Slates a Charge   Tied to Revamping of Unit</HL><DATE>12/23/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C19</SO><CO>   ML</CO><MS>TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)</IN><NS>EARNINGS PROJECTIONS (ERP)</NS><RE>MARYLAND (MD)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Martin Marietta Corp. said it will take a $39 millionfourth-quarter charge, equal to 78 cents a share, related torestructuring its unprofitable International Light Metalsoperations in California.   The Bethesda, Md., defense contractor said the after-taxcharge was being taken to cover estimated costs of a numberof options involving the unit, including leasing it toanother operator, selling it or shutting it down and sellingthe assets. A spokesman said a decision on which course totake would be made early next year.</LP><TEXT>   International Light Metals has sales of about $100 milliona year, just a fraction of Martin Marietta's overall annualsales of about $6 billion.   Martin Marietta Chairman Norman Augustine said therestructuring would &quot;improve the corporation's futureearnings stream and have minimal cash impact.&quot;   In the fourth quarter of 1990, Martin Marietta earned$57.2 million, or $1.17 a share, on sales of $1.56 billion.</TEXT></DOC>